"Ah, Telemachus, the dauntless orator, That's the spirit! No hard feelings now! Let's just eat and drink as we always have.
The townspeople will provide you with everything— A ship, a crew—to speed you on to sacred Pylos
In your search for news of your noble father." And Telemachus, drawing in his breath:
"Antinous, there is no way I can relax
Or enjoy myself with you arrogant bastards. Isn't it bad enough that you have eaten through Much of my wealth while I was still a child?
Now that I'm grown, and hear things from others, And get angrier and angrier at what I see and hear, I'm going to do my best to nail you to the wall, Either by going to Pylos or staying here in this land. But I am going, and I'll make the journey count, Even though I have to sail in another man's ship
And can't captain my own, which I'm sure suits you fine."

And he withdrew his hand from Antinous'. The suitors, busy with preparing the feast,
Jeered at him as they swaggered through the hall:

"Hey, everybody! Telemachus is planning to murder us! He'll bring reinforcements from sandy Pylos,
Or even from Sparta. He's really serious.
Or he'll go to Ephyre and get deadly poisons To put in our wine-bowl and kill us all."
 








