By Polycaste, Nestor's youngest daughter.
When this lovely girl had bathed him, rubbed him with oil, And thrown on his shoulders a tunic and cloak, Telemachus came forth like an immortal god
And took his seat beside Nestor, shepherd of the people.

When they had roasted the meat and drawn it Off the spits, they sat down and feasted,
Waited upon by worthy men who poured their wine Into golden cups. When they had enough
To eat and drink, Gerenian Nestor spoke:

"My sons, yoke the combed horses to the chariot So that Telemachus may begin his journey."

He spoke, and they did as he said,
Quickly yoking the horses. The housekeeper Placed in the chariot bread and wine
And the sort of fare kings and lords eat. Telemachus mounted the beautiful chariot, And Peisistratus, Nestor's son,
Stepped in beside him and took the reins. He flicked the lash and the horses took off, Eating up the plain and leaving behind them The high rock of Pylos. All day long
They jostled the yoke that held them together.

As the sun set and the world grew dark
They came to Pherae and pulled up at the house Of Diocles, son of Ortilochus,
 






