I found a ship, Phoenician, and made it Worth the crew's while to take me to Pylos,
Or Elis maybe, where the Epeans are in power. Well, the wind pushed us back from those shores— It wasn't their fault, they didn't want to cheat me— And we were driven here in the middle of the night And rowed like hell into the harbor. Didn't even
Think of chow, though we sure could have used some, Just got off the boat and lay down, all of us.
I slept like a baby, dead to the world,
And they unloaded my stuff from the ship's hold And set it down next to me where I lay on the sand. Then off they went to Sidonia, the big city,
And I was left here, stranded, just aching inside."

Athena smiled at him, her eyes blue as the sea, And her hand brushed his cheek. She was now A tall, beautiful woman, with an exquisite touch For handiwork, and her words had wings:

"Only a master thief, a real con artist, Could match your tricks—even a god Might come up short. You wily bastard, You cunning, elusive, habitual liar!
 

