And you answered him, Eumaeus, my swineherd:

 
"There's nothing wrong with your story, old man, And nothing you've said is out of line
Or unprofitable. So you won't go without. You'll have clothing, yes, and everything else A suppliant in need ought to receive—
At least for tonight. But in the morning
You'll have to shake out those old rags of yours. We don't have extra tunics or cloaks
Around here. Each man has only one.
But when Odysseus' son comes, he himself Will give you a cloak and tunic to wear,
And will send you wherever your heart desires."

So saying, the swineherd sprang to his feet And started to make up a bed for Odysseus
Near the fire, spreading it with goatskins and fleeces. There Odysseus lay down, and Eumaeus
Threw over him a large, heavy cloak
That he kept as a spare for stormy weather.

So there Odysseus slept, with the young men All around him. But not the swineherd.
He would not settle for a bed inside,
Away from the boars. He got himself ready To go sleep outdoors, and Odysseus was glad That he took such good care of the property Of his absent master. First, Eumaeus
Slung his sharp sword over his sturdy shoulders
 





550








555










560








