325
 
Odysseus and his cohorts were clubbing the suitors Right and left all through the hall; horrible groans Rose from their lips as their heads were smashed in, And the floor of the great hall smoked with blood.
It was then that Leodes, the soothsayer, rushed forward, Clasped Odysseus' knees, and begged for his life:

"By your knees, Odysseus, respect me
And pity me. I swear I have never said or done Anything wrong to any woman in your house.
I tried to stop the suitors when they did such things,
But they wouldn't listen, wouldn't keep their hands clean, And now they've paid a cruel price for their sins.
And I, their soothsayer, who have done no wrong, Will be laid low with them. That's the gratitude I get."

Odysseus scowled down at the man and said:

"If you are really their soothsayer, as you boast you are, How many times must you have prayed in the halls That my sweet homecoming would never come,
And that you would be the one my wife would go off with And bear children to! You're a dead man."

As he spoke his strong hand reached for a sword That lay nearby—a sword Agelaus had dropped When he was killed. The soothsayer was struck Full in the neck. His lips were still forming words When his lopped head rolled in the dust.
 




