"He's innocent; don't kill him. And let's spare the herald, Medon,
Who used to take care of me when I was a child, If Philoetius hasn't already killed him—
Or the swineherd—or if he didn't run into you As you were charging through the house."

Medon heard what Telemachus said.
He was under a chair, wrapped in an oxhide, Cowering from death. Now he jumped up, Stripped off the oxhide, ran to Telemachus And fell at his knees. His words rose on wings:

"I'm here, Telemachus! Hold back, and ask your father To hold back too, or he might kill me with cold bronze, Strong as he is and as mad as he is at the suitors,
Who ate away his house and paid you no honor." Odysseus smiled at this and said to him:
"Don't worry, he's saved you. Now you know, And you can tell the world, how much better Good deeds are than evil. Go outside, now, You and the singer, and sit in the yard
Away from the slaughter, until I finish Everything I have to do inside the house."

So he spoke, and the two went out of the hall And sat down by the altar of great Zeus,
Wide-eyed and expecting death at any moment.
 

